## Questions

- For atoms it is common to do numerical solution of the radial DE instead of using basis sets.
  Is there a way to fit that solution approach into the framework for this project?
  What if the radial solution is treated as an irrep basis set (IBS) with one basis function?
  An alternate implementation of `UpdateOrbitals` (`src/Orbitals/Internal/Imp/TOrbitals.C`) would then do a numerical radial
  solution for each irrep using the current charge density. I suspect there are many difficult details left out of my proposal.

## Major Features

### Convergence acceleration

- Done: Geometric Direct Minimization (GDM)
  - Read up on BFDS method, Numerical Recipes section 10.7
  - Make notes that translate into our notation.
  - The original paper is very hard to follow.
- DIIS singular B
  - Shprd & Minkoff 2007 eq 23. Linear Least Squares gives a much better condition number.
  - Consider SVD and truncating B.
- EDIIS

### DFT upgrade

- Hand code Vosko's exchange.
- Consider separate `Vxc`, `Vex`, and `Vcorr`.
- Reproducing the NIST tests is tricky (various formula ambiguities).

### Perturbation support

- OOD/SOLID architecture for handling perturbations (first and second order).
- Demo first order with SO-coupling for HF and DHF.
- Demo second order with Moller–Plesset (MP2).

### Configuration Interaction

- Full CI, Truncated, multi-reference
- Our goal is to demonstrate that our OO design or architecture supports it.
- Rank in terms of 
    1) code complexity for this project.  How much of current infrastructure needs to change?
    2) usefulness/popularity in the real world of users.

### Parallel execution

- Consider OpenMP; beware gprof output issues.
- Use LLVM profiling (`-fprofile-instr-generate`, `-fcoverage-mapping`) and Linux `perf` for profiling.
- Use parallel loops over 
    1) irreps for `AccumulateDirect` and `AccumulateExchange`.
    2) Hamiltonian terms??



