## Solids
- Lets use capital letters for SOLID OOD principles and lower case "solid" for solid materials with a periodic lattice stucture.
- This plan is about solids or lattices.
- Ultimate (abititious!) target: Something like VASP/ABINIT that handles (ultra soft) psuepotentials.
    Whether or not HF or DHF is supported is solely based on if the Evaluator for the basis set satisfies the
    concept constratints for those integrals.
- The infrastucture in qchem is only half set up for complex basis sets/Hamiltonians/Orbitals etc.
- We need to somehow seemlessly change between blaze::SymmetricMatrix and blaze::HermitianMatrix. 
- Aside: I like using dcmplx=std::complex<double>; ... it the same number of chars as double so things line up nicely in class
    interface.
- lets start the thought process with LASolver in mind.
    Can we conditionaly deduce (at compile time) hmat_t  from T such that
        hmat_t<double>=blaze::SymmetricMatrix<double> or
        hmat_t<dcmplx>=blaze::HermitianMatrix<dcmplx>
    Modern c++ must have a way to do this without doing partial class specializatons.
- Next we need a highly trivial 1 electron (no ERIs yet) plane wave problem in order to get solids off the ground.
    Maybe just a hydrogen cubic lattice.  At high lattice spacing we know energy should be ~-0.5au/unit_cell (?)
- We have BlockQN in the Symmetry library for wave vector irreps.
- We have UnitCell and Lattice in the Cluster library (maybe should be renamed Cluster->Stucture even though Atom is normally 
    thought of as a structure).  
- Once we have the demo problem up and running we can think about next steps.  There must some useful models that are intermediate in coding difficulty between PW and Pseudo potentials.

